review_blob: light golden colour, very low head, average start then the fizz goes, slightly sweet. The after taste is pungent and sweet.  It has a gentle and smooth consistancy. Your mouth goes a bit dry afterwards though.
flavourless beer, not much of anything really, has a decent mouthfeel, at least it doesn't leave you with a sore head...

well laced, some hoppy flavour, but mostly covered but the fizz and i guess a pleasant thiness/mouthfeel. sweetly bitter aftertaste. Always drank this at bbqs and trainings, serves the purpose well but never seen it out of a bottle.
nice clean beer, not much on flavour, crisp (throat complains after a few) but not so smooth. I somehow get a sugary sweet after taste drinkng this.....
looks less impressive... but who cares, the hoppy, caramel and more intense flavor and thicker texture beats Guinness draught anyday

good roasted aroma, thin and watery but, nice bitter and roasted flavour. The bottle(in Aus) had a little plastic cooler pill thingo inside which was amusing to discover. Looks awesome but loses marks on it being thin, maybe it's only the Australian version.

the colour of coke with a slight, biege head. The new bottles say 'Smooth Australian ale' and i absoulutly agree with this, it's carbonated at just the right amount and very palatable. sweet malty aroma but can also smell a little metallic (haven't made up my mind). Rich flavour with the coffee coming through at the start then being replaced by the malty flavour, then ending in a clean and smooth run leaving a nice roasted aftertaste. In my opinion better than a guiness draught. Great introduction to the dark side of beer of those who haven't ventured. Cheers.
It really wasn't that bad, a bit boring and plain, but nicely acidic and easy. And a good party ice breaker if you live on Tasman street

There's nothing bad that hasn't been said already (i'd like to stress the point that it seriously gives you a headach). I guess the positives to come out of this beer were that: it was cheap, and that it puts you to sleep have way through the bottle.

A better light beer than than most other labels can offer, a little pale and watery as with most lights, it was also a little too carbonated which made it harder to palate from a bottle. However, it does have a hoppy taste and as i said before, better than most lights by far
I really like the aroma of this, i think it has a slight fruity and hoppy smell to it. refreshing and clean to drink and just the right flavour. One of the best beers around.
like a VB but more refreshing and more hoppy, but of course, CUB does brew one big batch then ferments it separately according to each beer, so not really surprised.
good solid drink, average taste but good value, avoid drinking at room temp as it tastes thin and discontinuous, with a suspect aftertaste. a too bit sharp at the end.

weak, watery, beer was never meant to taste like bad water with bubbles and food colouring, absolute crap, i cringed at the thought of having to finish the bottle at a bbq, even stale non alcoholic beer tastes better.

This beer is becoming the most accessible and mass marketed beer in NSW, I don't see anything worth boasting about, it has an unusual and chemically bitter aftertaste and is the sort of stuff that gives you headaches not after long. The only reason most people that i know drink it is because of the advertising and the availability. Disappointingly poor
honey sweet flavour, I agree that there's something about the aroma that make it smell a bit acidic but the appearance is good and goes down very smoothly. Best beer by far at my uni bar
beer_name: James Squire Nine Tales Amber Ale
